        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">2.1 What the Institute Does</h2>

        <p>
          The Eighth Anchor Institute does five things. Not six. Not three.
          Five. Each program below has one job, one audience, one measurable
          output. The Institute is built to do these five things and nothing
          else.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">2.1.1 The Reference Library</h3>
        <p>
          The Library is the empirical floor. It is a continuously-maintained,
          citation-rich, publicly-accessible synthesis of the school-trust-lands
          fiduciary record across all twenty trust-lands states. Every claim
          cites a source. Every figure traces back to a statute, a court ruling,
          or a primary document. The AI-era trust architects are designing
          forever-institutions right now, and they have no comparable record to
          consult. Two hundred years of school-trust-lands experience is the
          only multi-generational fiduciary data the country has produced. The
          Library makes that record stand up under expert scrutiny. Part of it
          is already built at schooltrusts.net under the Advocates for School
          Trust Lands umbrella. The Institute is the next phase — institutional
          maintenance, citation curation, and original synthesis at a standard
          the architects will trust.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The Atlas.</strong> A page per state. Permanent fund corpus, distribution rate, breach history, and a current grade. Twenty states. Updated annually.</li>
          <li><strong>The Court Room.</strong> Every consequential Supreme Court and state-court case on school trust lands, annotated against the questions the AI-era trust architects are asking today.</li>
          <li><strong>The Reading Room.</strong> Academic, statutory, and primary-source bibliography across the field. The first stop for any serious researcher entering the topic.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">2.1.2 Quarterly Briefings on Specific AI-Era Trust Proposals</h3>
        <p>
          When a real AI-era trust proposal enters public design — a sovereign
          AI fund, a climate endowment, a longevity escrow — the Institute
          publishes a fifteen-to-twenty-page briefing. The briefing analyzes
          the proposal through the school-trust-lands failure-mode record. What
          is likely to drift over fifty years. What is likely to be hijacked.
          Which design choices the historical record warns against. The
          briefings go directly to the named architects, by name, by hand. They
          are short enough to read in a single sitting and specific enough to be
          useful in the design room.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Q3 2026, inaugural briefing.</strong> A proposed sovereign AI fund. Specific proposal to be selected once the Institute is operational.</li>
          <li><strong>Q4 2026.</strong> A perpetual climate endowment proposal.</li>
          <li><strong>Q1 2027.</strong> The longevity-escrow regulatory question.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">2.1.3 The Fellowship</h3>
        <p>
          The Fellowship is the recruitment mechanism dressed as a program.
          Each year a small cohort — three to five in the first year — of humans
          actively working on AI-era trust design spend a year engaged with the
          Institute as colleagues. They come from AI labs, foundations,
          advisory firms, regulatory bodies. They contribute the architect's
          perspective. The Institute contributes the empirical floor. Their
          work product is shared through the Institute's publications. The
          deeper purpose is straightforward: a fellow who has spent a year
          inside the Library becomes an advocate inside her own institution.
          That is how the message moves.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>A trust-and-estates attorney working on longevity-escrow regulation.</li>
          <li>A staff member at a major AI lab thinking through sovereign AI funding.</li>
          <li>A senior fellow at a long-horizon foundation.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">2.1.4 The Annual Convening</h3>
        <p>
          Once a year the Institute brings the small school-trust-lands
          subject-matter community and the AI-era trust architects into the
          same room for two days. The first Convening is held in fall 2027. It
          is a working conference, not a recruiting event. The agenda is built
          around live design questions the architects are facing. The people who
          have watched school trust funds drift for two centuries sit across the
          table from the people designing the funds that will run for the next
          two. The conversations that happen there cannot happen anywhere else.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>A joint statement issued at the close of the meeting.</li>
          <li>Follow-up working groups carried forward into the next year's briefings.</li>
          <li>A published proceedings volume in the Library.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">2.1.5 The Recruitment Engine</h3>
        <p>
          Recruitment runs across all four programs above. The Institute
          identifies architects working on relevant trusts. It brings them into
          the Library as readers. It invites them to fellowships and convenings.
          A small fraction joins the advisory board or the board itself. This is
          not a side activity. It is the primary distribution mechanism for the
          Institute's message. The architects are not a publishing audience to
          be reached through marketing. They are a network the Institute needs
          to be inside. Every Library page, every briefing, every fellowship,
          every convening is built with that recruitment function in view.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>A running list of named architects, by institution, with current engagement status.</li>
          <li>A direct-distribution pipeline for every briefing, by name, by hand.</li>
          <li>A pathway from first contact to advisory role to board seat, with measurable stages.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">2.2 First-Year Program (June 2026 — May 2027)</h2>

        <p>
          Twelve months. Six concrete milestones. The first year is the proof
          that the Institute can do what it says it does.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">Month 1 (June 2026): Founding charter ratified, board constituted</h3>
        <p>
          The founding charter is ratified and the board is seated. Minimum
          three founding board members: Dave Sullivan as Chairman, Tonia Day if
          she accepts, and Margaret Bird in either an advisory or founding
          capacity as her bandwidth permits. One external board member from
          outside the school-trust-lands world is recruited — an AI-policy
          figure or a fiduciary-law scholar — to keep the Institute honest
          about the audience it is built to serve. Output: a signed charter, a
          constituted board, a public announcement.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">Month 2 (July 2026): AI staff onboarded and operating</h3>
        <p>
          The Institute's AI staff comes online. Six initial roles across
          Research (Gemini and ChatGPT), Coding and Infrastructure (Codex CLI
          and Claude Code), Communications (ChatGPT), and Recruiting and
          Evaluation. A CTO role is established to track the frontier and
          trigger replacements when a better tool emerges. Each staff role has
          a written job description, a performance rubric, and a defined
          replacement trigger. Output: an operating org chart and a first
          month of measured performance against the rubrics.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">Month 3 (August 2026): First quarterly briefing drafted</h3>
        <p>
          The first quarterly briefing is drafted in full. Topic selected from
          live AI-era trust proposals under public discussion. The draft
          circulates to the founding board for review. Tonia and Margaret see
          the first sample of the briefing series before any public release.
          Output: a complete, reviewed draft and a decision to publish.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">Month 4 (September 2026): Quarterly Briefing #1 published</h3>
        <p>
          The Institute's first quarterly briefing is published. Public release
          plus direct distribution to the named architects of the proposal under
          analysis. This is the Institute's first major external output and the
          first test of whether the architects engage. Output: the published
          briefing, a distribution record, and a log of architect responses.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">Month 6 (November 2026): First fellowship cohort recruited</h3>
        <p>
          The first fellowship cohort is recruited and announced for 2027.
          Three to five fellows from AI labs, foundations, advisory firms, or
          regulatory bodies. Selection criteria favor architects actively
          working on live trust proposals. Output: a public cohort announcement
          and signed fellowship agreements.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">Month 9 (February 2027): Quarterly Briefing #2 published</h3>
        <p>
          The second quarterly briefing is published. Topic and method are
          informed by what the Institute learned from the architects' response
          to Briefing #1. Output: the published briefing and a written
          reflection on what shifted between the first and second.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">Month 12 (May 2027): First-year audit and Convening planning</h3>
        <p>
          The Institute publishes a first-year audit. Performance against the
          rubric for every program. What worked, what did not, what the
          Institute is changing. Planning for the fall 2027 Convening begins in
          the same month. Output: a public year-one report and a Convening
          date, location, and invitation list.
        </p>

